The basic unit we'll compare it to is thiophene, which has a melting point of -38°C. The presence of two phenyl rings will significantly increase the melting point due to the increase in the pi-pi stacking and van der Waals interactions; each phenyl ring could contribute approximately +40°C to the melting point. The tertiary amine groups typically reduce the melting point due to the introduction of nitrogen, which can disrupt the crystal lattice; however, the effect in this molecule is mitigated because they are part of a larger, more rigid structure. The tertiary amine groups might reduce the melting point by about -5°C each. Prediction:

Alkyl chain contributions: 2 x +2°C (ethyl groups) + 2 x +1°C (methyl groups) = +6°C. 
Predicted melting point: -38 + 80 - 10 + 6 = 38°C
